The White House has released a report stating that 28 states are making progress in implementing Affordable Insurance Exchanges, which are a key component of health care reform. These exchanges are state-based marketplaces where consumers can choose a private health insurance plan that fits their needs. The report highlights actions taken by some states, such as Alabama creating the Alabama Health Insurance Marketplace and Colorado establishing the Colorado Health Insurance Exchange. The report also mentions the steps taken by the Obama Administration to ensure access to exchanges for all Americans by developing the necessary technology and business systems. The report emphasizes that the implementation of exchanges is just one way states are implementing health reform, with other actions including enforcing patient protections and improving prevention and public health. The Affordable Care Act has already had a positive impact, with millions of young adults gaining insurance, seniors receiving discounts on prescription drugs, and insurance companies being prohibited from dropping coverage or imposing lifetime caps on care.